<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[512, 366, 911, 536]]<|/det|>
Marshall speaker achieves the best success rate, which is close to \(100\%\) (6/7) for Echo and \(100\%\) (7/7) for Cortana. The value drops to \(42.9\%\) (3/7) and \(85.7\%\) (6/7) at \(50\mathrm{cm}\) . When the distance reaches \(2\mathrm{m}\) , the success rates are \(14.3\%\) (1/7) and \(54.1\%\) (4/7). Despite the performance degradation, ALIF- OTA still achieves a success rate of higher than \(50\%\) in the challenging \(2\mathrm{m}\) distance. To the best of our knowledge, this is the longest attack distance in studies on black- box audio attacks (same as Devil's Whisper). NICCCAM [9], which has a similar scenario to ours, achieved a success rate of \(60\%\) on Cortana at a distance of \(15\mathrm{cm}\) and was not evaluated for performance at a longer distance.  

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[512, 536, 911, 691]]<|/det|>
Evaluation of ambient noise. We evaluate the robustness of our attack against ambient noise by launching our examples across various levels of white noise. As Table 6 illustrates, our examples demonstrate strong performance at a signal- to- noise ratio (SNR) of roughly \(20\mathrm{dB}\) and above, similar to soft speech, but performance diminishes with an increase in ambient noise. This aligns with the SNR level reported in Devil's Whisper [8] and When Evil Calls [11]. Notably, even with a decrease in SNR to \(3\mathrm{dB}\) , we can still achieve a success rate of more than \(40\%\) when attacking Echo. This emphasizes the robustness of our attack.  

